  "prompt": "Why are there two capital letters in the surname McCall?",
  "response": "The surname \"McCall\" originates from the Gaelic \"Mac Cathmhaoil,\" which means \"son of Cathmhaoil.\" In Gaelic, \"Mac\" means \"son of,\" and it is often used as a prefix in surnames. Over time, the prefix was abbreviated and combined with the following name, leading to the format \"Mc\" or \"Mac.\" The capital \"C\" in \"McCall\" is a convention in English to indicate the start of the second part of the compound surname, making it easier to read and preserving the original structure of the name. This style is common in many surnames with prefixes like \"Mc\" or \"O',\" where the prefix denotes lineage or ancestry.",
